Findings and resolutions:

| Finding | Severity | Resolution |
| --- | --- | --- |
| ADR-004 could overclaim Eve compatibility before P00-T08. | Critical | ADR-004 explicitly says P00-T08 has not validated compatibility and must validate public contracts and fallback policy before production defaults bind to Eve. |
| ADR-004 needed a provider-neutral core boundary. | Critical | ADR-004 states core domain types and board/policy/evidence entities must not import Eve types or rely on private Eve internals. |
| ADR-005 needed at-least-once assumptions and explicit dedupe rules for non-idempotent effects. | Critical | ADR-005 defines at-least-once delivery, event IDs, idempotency keys, outbox rules, side-effect classes, and per-effect approval or dedupe rules. |
| ADR-005 needed to distinguish event replay from model re-execution. | Critical | ADR-005 defines replay as projection rebuild from events and re-execution as a new or resumed model/tool run with new records. |
| ADR-006 risk tiers could remain subjective if examples did not map to deterministic gates. | Critical | ADR-006 includes scoring inputs, thresholds, hard floors, mandatory gates, override authority, and deterministic examples. |
| ADR-006 could let a low score weaken charter protections. | Critical | ADR-006 states risk gates may increase protections but may not silently decrease constitution, charter, security, or protected-oracle requirements. |
| ADR-007 needed to include every current v8 `/legion:*` command, not just the transformation-plan subset. | Critical | ADR-007 includes all 19 current command files with keep, rename, alias, or remove disposition. |
| ADR-007 needed to avoid confusing operational Kanban with governance deliberation. | Critical | ADR-007 reserves board for operational Kanban and council for governance deliberation, with `/legion:board` renamed to council in v9. |

Side-effect and idempotency review summary:
- Event handlers assume at-least-once delivery.
- Outbox intent, event append, and state transition share one transaction.
- S2 Git effects require dedupe by tree, parent, message, tag name, target, branch, and change ID as applicable.
- S3 external reversible effects require provider target plus logical key dedupe and approval when visibility or user impact is material.
- S4 destructive or hard-to-reverse effects require explicit human approval plus dedupe, dry-run, rollback, or recovery evidence where practical.
- No non-idempotent side effect remains without an approval or dedupe rule.

Risk-tier test cases summary:

| Case | Expected tier | Mandatory gates |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Typo in committed docs | R0 | Deterministic docs check and evidence note. |
| Isolated internal utility refactor with tests | R1 | Task contract, deterministic verification, evidence, lightweight review. |
| User-facing CLI command touching multiple modules | R3 by total score in ADR example, or no lower than R2 by user-facing floor if overridden | Spec/oracle/review/integration gates unless audited override applies. |
| Persistent board migration | R3 | Migration oracle, dry-run, rollback or forward-fix evidence, review, approval. |
| Production credential rotation | R3 | Security review, explicit approval, outbox, recovery evidence, observation. |

Command migration map summary:
- Current v8 commands reviewed: 19.
- `board` governance collision resolved by renaming governance to `council`.
- Operational Kanban uses `legion board`.
- v8 `/legion:review` keeps the review concept as `legion review`.
- v8 `/legion:update` is removed from the v9 workflow surface because package updates are not project work-control state.
